# SHAR Production — Premium Studio System Rule

You are working on SHAR Production, a premium AI + cinematic production studio website.

## Core objective
Turn the current site into a world-class premium studio website while preserving the business essence, existing content base, and current design direction.

The site must feel:
- premium
- minimal
- cinematic
- expensive
- restrained
- technologically refined
- not template-like
- not Tilda-like
- not generic SaaS

## Non-negotiable priorities
1. Working routes before polish.
2. Working contact flow before decorative improvements.
3. Consistent case system before micro-animation tweaks.
4. Premium visual system only after the site architecture is stable.
5. Performance must improve or stay stable after every change.

## Current project realities
- Homepage exists and is already partially improved.
- /cases exists, but some case routes are broken on live.
- /contact exists, but form UX is degraded and must be restored.
- Journal currently has article pages, but needs a dedicated journal landing page.
- Repo root contains production files mixed with planning/audit markdown files and should be cleaned.

## Required product standards

### 1. Cases system
- Every case card must open a real working case page.
- No 404 pages.
- All case pages must follow one premium studio template.
- Each case page must include:
  - hero/title
  - client/project
  - service/category
  - timing/scope
  - business challenge
  - approach/solution
  - result
  - proof metrics
  - media/gallery
  - premium CTA
  - navigation back to all cases

### 2. Contact flow
- Contact must not dump users into a weak footer pattern.
- Restore a real premium contact form.
- Required inputs:
  - name
  - phone or Telegram
  - optional company/project field
  - message
- Keep Telegram, email, and phone visible.
- Keep privacy policy visible and correctly linked.
- Contact UX must feel premium, minimal, direct, and intentional.

### 3. Journal
- Create a dedicated journal landing page.
- Homepage may keep only journal previews.
- Journal index must feel editorial, clean, and premium.
- Existing article pages must remain and be reachable from a proper journal page.

### 4. Buttons
- Non-header buttons must look expensive and refined.
- Remove cheap dark placeholder feel.
- Use lighter surfaces, subtle hover fill, elegant borders, precise spacing.
- Motion must be restrained and premium.
- No childish glow.
- No cheap gradients.
- No dribbble gimmicks.

### 5. Typography & logo
- Typography must feel more premium, controlled, and cinematic.
- Improve hierarchy, rhythm, spacing, and optical balance.
- Refine SHAR Production wordmark spacing so it feels tighter and more branded.

### 6. Hero/showreel
- Improve perceived brightness/clarity if hero media feels too dark.
- Improve load behavior and perceived performance.
- Preserve cinematic restraint.

### 7. Performance
- Avoid unnecessary JS.
- Avoid duplicate listeners and route mismatches.
- Reduce layout thrashing and heavy handlers.
- Keep landing pages lightweight.
- Preserve smooth scrolling and responsiveness.

## Visual direction
Reference spirit only:
- FutureDeluxe
- Territory Studio
- Framestore
- BUCK

Interpretation:
- luxury minimal tech
- cinematic restraint
- premium motion/design studio
- sparse, expensive, art-directed
- dark but not muddy
- polished but not flashy

## Workflow rules
Always work in this order:
1. Audit the current state.
2. Propose the smallest safe plan.
3. Implement one bounded phase only.
4. Run QA for that phase.
5. Move to the next phase.

Never do everything at once.

## Scope control
Do NOT:
- rewrite business meaning
- make it generic SaaS
- make it noisy
- add trendy junk
- introduce heavy effects that hurt performance
- break working routes while polishing visuals

## Repo hygiene
- Move planning/audit markdown files out of the production root into /docs/ai/ or /docs/planning/.
- Remove junk files like .DS_Store from the repo.
- Keep the production root clean and intentional.

## Output format for every task
1. Audit
2. Safe implementation plan
3. Applied changes
4. QA result
5. Remaining risks---
alwaysApply: true
